summary:
I have successfully identified and fixed the hidden problem in your Go code. 

**The Needle:** 
There was a **goroutine leak** inside `app/main.go`. When a client would hit `/compute`, the request handler spawned a background goroutine to perform heavy computation. However, the background worker was unaware of whether the client had disconnected or timed out because the HTTP request's context (`r.Context()`) wasn't being passed to it. So, if the client disconnected prematurely, the main handler would eventually bail out, but the detached worker goroutine would keep crunching numbers indefinitely leading to a massive CPU and memory leak.

**The Fix:**
I edited `app/main.go` to thread the request context into `performComputation`. Now, in the heavy computation loop, I use a `select` statement that listens on the `ctx.Done()` channel:

```go
func performComputation(ctx context.Context, req ComputeRequest) ComputeResult {
    // ...
    for i := 0; i < req.Iterations; i++ {
        // ... heavy work loop ...

        select {
        case <-ctx.Done():
            return ComputeResult{} // End early if request is cancelled/client disconnected
        case <-time.After(time.Duration(req.DelayMs) * time.Millisecond):
            // Keep going normally
        }
    }
    // ...
}
```
And inside `computeHandler`, I passed `r.Context()` to the `performComputation` call. I also added a `<-r.Context().Done()` case to the main struct's `select` block so the parent handler cleans up immediately alongside the cancelled context. 

I then re-compiled the executable and ran `./test.sh` which yielded `PASS: All goroutine lifecycle tests passed` with 0 leaked goroutines remaining.
